Why yes!  The NSWR!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
When you boil it down to its basics, an NSWR is a tank of saltwater, a reliable pump, and a reaction nozzle.  Not too much challenging there.    Heck, if you REALLY want to dumb it down, you can replace the pump with a can of compressed air and a butterfly valve.  It's nuclear plumbing, fer pete's sake.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Anything like the same performance? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, the NSWR.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  45% IMLEO being cargo, on a ~100km/sec delta-V, 6 week trajectory to Mars? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, the NSWR.  If you are willing to ground launch an Orion, you would be willing to ground launch an NSWR.  NOTE!  I advocate NTR's as boosters, but NOT the NSWR.  Risk mitigation only goes so far.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Using 20 percent U235 fuel, the exhaust velocity of the NSWR is calculated at 66 km/sec.  Using a simple conversion, 66 km/sec * 102 yields a Isp of 6732.  This is with 3 MILLION pounds of thrust!  YIKES!<br>
<br>
If you use the really aggressive 95 percent U235 (which the Orion uses in most instances, BTW) then the calculated Isp soars to a huge 479,400 seconds due to the exhaust speed raging along at 4700 km/sec.<br>
<br>
A simple rule of thumb I like to use is this:  The total DeltaV you can attain using 40 percent of your ship mass as fuel is equal to half the exhaust velocity.  <br>
<br>
So, using 40 percent of the ship for fuel, and 15 percent for dead mass, an NSWR using the high enrichment, high octane fuel can deliver a 45 percent cargo fraction with a total deltaV of 2,350 km/sec.  Or, about ten high-energy round trips to Mars and back to Earth, landing at both ends, without refueling.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Trust me, the Orion concept is obsolete.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  With technology readily understood in the '50s!?!? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think they had plumbing and pumps and valves in the 50's.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Operating an NSWR is stone simple, all the elegance is in the design.  Thank you, big computers!  <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I like Magsails. Not the same understood tech, not the same performance (Low thrust/mass, although miraculous performance for that) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
