As threatened, I posted my thoughts for a NTR powered launcher.  I did not want to pull this thread off topic, so I put it in <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessage?topicID=133.topic"> this one </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> instead.<br>
<br>
As a note, if you are going to go interstellar without breaking the laws of physics too much, a lightsail boosted antimatter powered design using a magnetic ramscoop to gain reaction mass from the interstellar medium is the way to go in my opinion.   Use the lasers on the light sail to get to .4 or .5 c, dump the sail, accelerate to .7 c using antimatter.  Then deploy the ramscoop to sweep up more reaction mass and start decelerating, then use the antimatter rocket to stop at the end.<br>
<br>
The trip back is slower, since you only have onboard power to make the trip.<br>
<br>
With an outbound average speed of .5 c and an average return speed of .2 c a round trip to a star up to 10 lightyears away should be doable in less than 60 years.<br>
<br>
Not too shabby! <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A> at: 9/14/02 2:48:00 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/10/02 12:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Interstellar daydreams</span><hr size=1> I'm just posting a brief response here because quite honestly I think anything more would only serve to elicit the same general ideas from me and the same responses back.<br>
<br>
So I just want to clarify an earlier statement made by me:<br>
<br>
I'm not morally objected to using nuclear technologies for space travel.  My moral objections lie in using nuclear BOMBS.<br>
<br>
<br>
Nuclear has been put to enough bad uses on this planet.  I personally think any trip to a new planet, or even star, should involve and new beginning for humanity and relations among different people.  Use it as a unifying factor, bringing together all of humanity.<br>
<br>
I do not think that nuclear bombs being available would aid in this process.  Nor do I think that they have the level of control that is desireable for fully reliable spaceflight.<br>
<br>
I would much rather see a fast-fission reactor witha multi-phase heat capture system, or even an antimatter-fusion or antimatter-fission hybrid reactor.<br>
