<br>
By controllable, I meant the bombs themselves.  The ratings they are given are nominal yields, for one things, and are not exact.  <br>
<br>
The handling of nuclear weapons, for the most part, is done really well.  But don't assume it's been perfect; I've heard some rather interesting stories involving accidents occuring that involved planes with nuclear weapons on their wings, and also other accidents occuring where the basic end effect is &quot;wow...uh, that was a nuke.  I thought it was conventional.&quot;  Nothing ever came of them, but the possibly is there.<br>
<br>
Regardless, I'm sure the handling of the bombs would be more than adequately secure from interference and error.  My concern is that as you detonate warheads and try to use their energy yield for calculations, they aren't an exact thing.  Variations of multiple kilotons of yield could be a serious issue for propulsion and navigation calculations.<br>
<br>
<br>
Thinking about it...there's another good question.  The EMP fields set up by these detonations would be rather detrimental to navigation sensors and communications equipment, even assuming it was shielding from the ships' systems. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 206<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 5:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=68>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion is plagued with bogeymen...</span><hr size=1> We've been around &amp; around the EMP question. I consider it a non-issue, so maybe I've not paid as much attention to the details of it as I should. Nevertheless, I stand by my original assumption:<br>
